<h3>So, how do we achieve this? </h3>
<p>
	Consider potatoes (I promise to get to polynomial in few seconds). Potatoes exhibit different properties in different conditions. It softens when you boil it or gets crispy when you fry it.  <br/><br/>
	
	The point being cooks use these properties to make delicious food like mashed potatoes or potato fries. In the same way, we need to understand polynomials and their properties. Once we know them, we can use them to build things that can solve real-world problems. In our case, an encryption system. <br/><br/>
</p>

<h3>What are polynomials?</h3>
<p>
	The term "poly" means many and nomials means "terms". Hence polynomials mean many terms. Let me give you a real-world example.  <br/><br/>
	
	Consider you are in a supermarket to do some shopping to make a potato dish. You want to calculate the price of the items you have purchased. Here's how you would do that.  <br/><br/>
	
	

	Total Cost = 3(price of each kg of potatoes) + 2(price of each cheese packet) + 1 (price of the cooking oil)  <br/><br/>
	
	Let's shorten the above equation.  <br/><br/>
	
	Total Cost = 3(p) + 2(c) + 1(o), this is what mathematicians call a polynomial. Though you might not be familiar with the term, you have been using it all along. <br/><br/>
	
	Say, you the price of one kg of potatoes is $3, each packet of cheese cost $0.40. and cooking oil costs $2. Now, let's put them in the equation.  <br/><br/>
	
	Total Cost = 3(3) + 2(0.40) + 1(2) = $11.80  <br/><br/>
	
    Now that we know a polynomial, let's visualize it, to understand more ideas about it.  <br/><br/>  
</p>

