<p>
	
	As the degree of x increases, we notice that the shape of the line becomes complex. Here degree means the highest power of x in a given equation (Ex: The equation x3 + x2 + 2x + 1, has the degree 3).<br/><br/>
	
	Hence curves and surfaces can be represented with such polynomial functions. <br/><br/>

	Cool, onto the idea or property of the polynimial that will help us with encryption. <br/><br/>

	You have seen how given an equation, we can generate points by substituting values for a term. In the rent equation, the substituion was for the "No. of Years Rented". <br/><br/>

	We can also do the opposite of it. Given a set of points, we can find the equation (This is proved by the polynimal interopolation theorem). <br/><br/>
</p>
