<p> Once you have this equation, you can predict the price for any year. Say you want to find the value for the 6th year, substitute x with 6. </p>
<h3>So why is that useful in encryption?</h3>
<p>
	There's one thing I didn't tell you. For a given set of points, the equation that exists is unique. So, even a small change in the points results in a different equation.<br/><br/>
    
	<img src="explained.png" style="width:100%;padding:100px" />
	
	Hence we can create a polynomial equation embed the secret inside it. Then encrypt or deconstruct it to individual points. These individual points can be distributed as secrets to different people. Since, we know mathematically they can only be reconstructed if all points come together, we know it's safe. <br/><br/>
	
	This helps us embed a secret in an equation. Say George's attack strategy code for 944. He can use the following equation. (There's a reason why we are not making 944 a coefficient, we will get to that soon.)<br/><br/>
	
	944 - 556x + 1123x<sup>2</sup> <br/><br/>
	
	Now he can generate points by equating different values of x other than 0. <br/><br/>
	
	Because if we equate 0, then <br/><br/>
	
	 944 - 556(0) + 1123(0)<sup>2</sup>= 944 will give away the secret.<br/><br/>
	
	So let's calculate for values 1,2 & 3.<br/><br/>
	
	(1, 944 - 556(1) + 1123(1)<sup>2</sup>) or (1, 1511)<br/><br/>
	(2, 944 - 556(2) + 1123(2)<sup>2</sup>) or (2, 4324)<br/><br/>
	(3, 944 - 556(3) + 1123(3)<sup>2</sup>) or (3, 9383)<br/><br/>
	
	All of these three points are required to construct the original equation and retrieve the secret. According to the theorem, it's impossible to recover the polynomial with just one or two points. <br/><br/>
	
	Hence George can share them separately with his generals. They can be only reconstructed when there's consensus between them.<br/><br/>
	
	But, how do we reconstruct the equation and retrieve the secret with a set of points?<br/><br/>
	
	We can use this formula to reconstruct the equation. Once we have the equation, we just equate the x with 0, and we will get the secret. <br/><br/>
   <span id="deconstructionEquation">\( y1\) \( (x-x2) (x-x3)\over (x1-x2)(x1-x3) \)  \( + y^2\)  \( (x-x1) (x-x3)\over (x2-x1)(x2-x3) \)  \( + y^3\)  \( (x-x1) (x-x2)\over (x3-x1)(x3-x2) \) </span><br/><br/>
	   <span id="deconstructionEquationSubstitutedStep1">\( 1511\) \( (x-2) (x-3)\over 2 \)  \( + 4324\)  \( (x-1) (x-3)\over -1 \)  \( + 9383\)  \( (x-1) (x-2)\over 2 \) </span><br/><br/>
	   <span id="deconstructionEquationSubstitutedStep2">\( 1123 x^2 - 556 x + 944 \)</span><br/><br/>
	   Now you can equate x with zero and you will get your secret. <br/><br/>
	   <span id="deconstructionEquationSubstitutedStep3">\( 1123 (0)^2 - 556(0) + 944 \)</span><br/><br/>
	   <span id="deconstructionEquationSubstitutedStep3">\( 944 \)</span><br/><br/>

I hope that was fun, if you are interested in the more tutorials like these, <a href="http://eepurl.com/g1aJ_f" >sign up here</a>.
</p>
